We came here on Saturday to celebrate V-Day. We had a reservation for inside but when arrived were told it would be at least 10 minutes or we could choose to be set outside. Much like that older couple in Indiana Jones The last Crusade, we chose poorly.  The tents outside were covered but only the corner heating elements were on - the umbrella-shaped heaters that delivered most of the heat had to be turned on. We were first to be sat outside so totally understand that. On this night, the heaters were not sufficient and we ate the entire meal in our coats and scarves. Though at one point I seriously considered taking the scarf to put under my legs - which were numb after the appetizers due to the effectiveness of the metal chairs on which we sat to wick away any heat. They really need to add cushions to mitigate this problem.  We ordered the Empanadas and Chorizo to start. Both were very tasty - the chorizo surprisingly so since it looked exactly like a hotdog (do not let this deter you, it was maybe the best dish we ordered). For our entree we split the Ribeye which we ordered medium rare but came out more on the medium side. It came.with julienned Veggies and Mashed Potatoes. The Mashed Potatoes were great and the veggies were fine, it a bit overcooked for my liking.  We wrapped dinner up with a Creme Brulee and two spoons. The creme brulee was good but at that point we were so frozen we just wanted to get the check and get on our way. It took 20 minutes from asking for the check to being able to leave the restaurant. I had to repeatedly ask for water (to be fair, I drink water like a camel so expect to ask at least a few times) but there were times I had to ask 2 and 3 times before my glass was refilled.
I booked a reservation for Valentines 3 days before and they canceled it at last minute when there are full restaurants everywhere .

We were sat in a private  little corner by the window, and were immediately impressed by the ambiance. It was crowded, but quiet. Our bubbly young waitress was almost over-attentive and as sweet as can be. We ordered the "traditional meal" for the two of us and we were brought a plate of perfectly and authentically Argentine cooked meat that was not only out of this world, but probably could have fed three or four people. We will most certainly make our way back to Malbec on our next trip to D.C.

Let's start by saying that is expensive for the quality of food. Cons: the bread was old and I had to throw it away since it felt like I was eating a rock. The molleja wasn't cook all the way and it had a lot of fiber so I also had to throw some of it away, you don't want to eat it uncooked. The Pollo a la Parrilla had a lot of wine and did not taste like it was cook a la parrilla. If you order to go like we did you better ask for silverware and napkins, they do not put it in the bag. The provoleta did not taste like it, not sure if  it was the real thing. The espinaca and cheese was bad as well for my taste. Pros: the Milanesa de Pollo was really good. The Ensalada was good, it need it salt but it was OK. I will recommend it only if you don't find something better, I wouldn't come back.
